<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-934-604  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 934 604.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Nov 30 1989 v34 n24A pS37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>First-generation drives focus on magneto-optics.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yazawa, Takeshi.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The first generation of rewritable optical disk drives are capableof storing video information and demonstrate potential fornetwork-server environments.andP;  The optical disk's removabilitygives it a distinct advantage over fixed-disk magnetic drivetechnology.andP;  The leading form of rewritable optical media today ismagneto-optical (MO), a technology that combines magnetic andlaser technology to read, write and erase/rewrite data.andP;  Close tothe techniques employed in conventional magnetic storage, MOtechnology involves the writing of digital information on themagnetic layers of a disk as a series of flux reversals.andP;  In orderto reverse the bit polarity, the MO drive's laser heats thesurface, transforming the magnetic properties and allowing thedrive's magnet to alter the direction of the bit.andP;  Rewritableoptical disk drives provide an efficient balance of storage costand performance capability.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TechnologyMagneto-Optical Disk DrivesOptical Disks.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Changing the bit's magnetic direction. (chart)Laser function in disk rotation process. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>